attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, Intel 80386, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, stripped

crowdsourced_ids_results.rule_raw: alert ( gid:116; sid:58; rev:2; msg:"(tcp) experimental TCP options found"; metadata: policy max-detect-ips drop, rule-type decode; classtype:protocol-command-decode;)

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The binary is a DDoS bot. It daemonizes itself by forking (syscall 2 in `sub_804f3f1`), creating a new session (`setsid`, syscall 0x42 in `sub_804f66d`), and redirecting its standard I/O to `/dev/null`. It spoofs its process name using `prctl` (syscall 0xac in `sub_804f583`). The core malicious activity involves creating raw network sockets (syscall 0x66 in `sub_805179f`) and executing highly complex, obfuscated functions (e.g., `sub_804a731`) to generate and send crafted packets, indicative of various network flood attacks.
